I haven't been able to ship this guitar since completeting it a month or so ago, as its owner has been traveling, and then this corona thing happened (shipping is back to normal now though!) So rather then just let the guitar collect dust I've been adding layers oil most days, to pull abit more out of the grain, and frankly I think it's starting to look rediculous.

I realised that lately I've been posting quite finished looking guitars, and less about the process. To be honest it's a bit scary, and makes me feel a bit vulnerable, showing what happens behind the scenes of a workshop. There's always mistakes, stuff to sand out, problems to solve, and mess. Lots of mess.
So I thought I should face my fears by showing one of these mistakes (or rather "design through process" ) on this hollow P bass I'm currently working on.

I like deep arm cuts on all my instruments, so I gave this guy the same treatment, but oh snap, I accidentally carved into the position where the bridge is going.

So one of my apprentices spent today carving a piece of bubinga (to match the fretboard) to act as a spacer between the curved body and the bridge. We will come up with a nice shape for it tomorrow to turn it into a design feature. It'll probably end up being the thing that I like the most about this build. It's often the f*~kups that end up being a projects best feature!

OK so who wants one of these?

@onkelamplified is making me a beast of an amp to have in the workshop, as my main demoing/testing guitars amp. I told him I liked to quickly test guitars by playing them painfully loud, and clean, to check for any buzzes coming through, hum, microphonic feedback, etc etc. It just helps to do it loud. 
As an aside I said "do you know what would be cool, a matching pedal board" and he's only gone and done it! He's built me a custom pedal board made from the same wood as the amp cabinet, and it looks incredible. 
So I'm asking you, what pedals do you want to see on my board for when I'm demoing guitars? It could be good to cover most bases for classic drives and mods.

What say you?

One thing that I think separates guitars made in small workshops like mine, to factory made guitars are details like this.

When I'm looking at a piece of wood that I have selected to use for a body, assessing where to cut and carve,  I'm always thinking ahead about what kind of grain pattern I want to emphasise, what grain I have to work with, and where I want to place it on the body. I don't just slap a piece of wood into a cnc machine and press play. (although I do have a cnc machine and for some things they are absolutely fantastic!) It makes my belly cuts quite sexy.

What do you lot think about this idea?

I would love to sell a more affordable guitar, around 850usd / 700gbp / 810eur (ish)

I've been thinking long and hard about how to make it work, without compromising on the quality. What's important to me is fantastic wood, stainless steel frets perfectly set up, handwound pickup with great tones, good tuning stability, comfortable to play and a hard wearing instrument that will just work for years. 
I've been in touch with some European factories, but I just can't get passionate about the idea of selling a "factory made" guitar.

So I had the idea of selling them without finish applied. This way it saves me lots and lots over time applying finish, and it gives you the control of how, and where you want the finish, and if you even want it at all. I will include a small bottle of Moar Magic Finishing oil, enough to apply to your guitar, in the sale, along with a demo vid of how to apply it.

What do you think? Would you be willing to commit to  getting ine by placing a deposit? I'm limiting the first batch of them to just 10.

WOW I've been overwhelmed by the interest in the "stripped down" Mortys!

So to clarify a few details, on this first batch I'm letting you choose pickup location, from neck, middle, or bridge, but I am only offering a single P90, with single volume. These aren't full on custom guitars, if you want that, you're welcome to order one of my regular, finished Mortys! 
Fretboard radius will be 12" and nut width is 42mm. Stainless steel medium jumbo frets.

To reserve a guitar I need 150usd / 150eur / 150gbp as a deposit. Expected waiting time is around 8 to 10 weeks. The deposit will be taken from the 850usd / 700gbp / 810eur bill. 
You can select body woods from Ash and mahogany, neck woods from maple or mahogany and either rosewood or ebony for the fretboard.

Prices do not include Vat. If you are within the EU I will (unfortunately) need go charge it, and shipping will be extra too.

I've sold 6 of the 10 I'm limiting this batch to in the past 4 hours.

Had a very cool visit today from fellow Copenhagen local, Archelaos. He's the man behind @bluefxdevices and promised to bring along a few pedals for me to try.

He arrived by bicycle (as is the norm here in Copenhagen) but had a breadboard of an oscillating fuzz pedal in his front bike rack. How authentic and cool is that!?! Anyway he left me one of his Nebula drive pedals to put on my new workshop board. It sounds great, very fat and round with a smooth high end, even at high gain settings. It also adds very little hum to the signal which is nice.

Looking forward to testing it lots moar.

These guitars aren't actually that thin. They just have big arm and belly cuts, giving a very thin profile on the upper side of the body.

They are around 45mm (so around 1.7") thick at the centre of the body, so they still have a very good acoustic tone. I A/B'd some Wayfairs again 330s and interestingly mine were quite a lot louder (acoustically). I put a lot of effort into making my Wayfairs as resonant as possible.
